Appendage unbranched, sometimes very elongated (up to 460 µm, Majewski 1994b ), consisting of several superposed and variably elongated cells. Antheridia stout, sessile or subsessile (on small supporting cells) ( Fig. 51A , arrows), not rarely on a short, ramified branch ( Fig. 51B , arrow) borne on the inner side of the lower cells of appendage, including cell III ( Fig. 51A , III) or, less commonly, above it up to the 10 th cell and even beyond. [Detailed descriptions: Majewski 1994b ;
Castaldo et al. 2004
]
